{[show S]A strong, balanced 1NT opening, and the partnership has slam in its sights. With a balanced hand and no major to investigate, responder turns to Gerber to count the partnership's aces before committing to six.
[BID 4C] Your partner opens 1NT, showing a balanced fifteen to seventeen. ⟦You have the values to drive past game and no major to show, so bid 4\C, Gerber. 4\C asks how many aces opener holds, and the answers climb a fixed ladder: 4\D shows zero or four aces, 4\H one, 4\S two, 4NT three. A later 5\C would ask for kings the same way.⟧
[BID 6N] Your partner answers 4\S, showing two aces. ⟦Two aces shown and the others at home, so all four are present and you raise to 6NT, in no danger of two cashing aces off the top.⟧
[show NS]South held \SAQ8 \HKQ6 \DJ5 \CAK963, nineteen with two aces of its own. Opener's 4\S showed the other two, so with every ace accounted for 6NT was never at risk and rolled home all thirteen tricks. When Gerber confirms the full set, the only question left is strength, and the partnership had plenty.}
