{[show S]Now the awkward rung. 4\D shows zero OR four aces, and the asker must read which from its own hand.
[BID 4C] Your partner opens 1NT, fifteen to seventeen balanced. ⟦You have the strength for slam with no major, so bid 4\C, Gerber.⟧
[BID 6N] Your partner answers 4\D, the ambiguous step, showing either zero aces or all four. ⟦Holding no ace itself, the asker reads 4\D as four, since zero would leave the partnership without a single ace, so you bid 6NT with every ace present.⟧
[show NS]South held \SKQ \HQ98 \DKQ74 \CKQ73, seventeen in kings and queens with no ace at all. That very absence resolves the ambiguity: partner's 4\D had to be four aces, so 6NT was cold and made thirteen. When you hold no ace, a 4\D answer can only be the big one.}
